        <h1>Math Question Bank 2078 - 2078</h1>
        <p><strong>Full Marks:</strong> 80 + 20</p>
        <p><strong>Pass Marks:</strong> 32 + 8</p>
        <p><strong>Time:</strong> 3 hours</p>
    <h2>Group A: Attempt any THREE Questions</h2><h3>Question 1(a)</h3>
<div><p><p>If \(f(x) = \sqrt{x}\) and \(g(x) = \sqrt{3 – x}\) then find f0g and its domain and range.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>f(x) = √x</p>
<p>\(g(x) = \sqrt{3-x}\)</p>
<p>fog(x) = ?</p>
<p>We know,</p>
<p>fog = f[g(x)] = f(\(\sqrt{3-x}\)</p>
<p>\(= \sqrt{\sqrt{3-x}}\)</p>
<p>\(= (3-x)^{\frac{1}{4}}\)</p>
<p><strong>Domain:</strong></p>
<p>To find domain of fog,</p>
<p>First we have to find domain of \(g(x) = \sqrt{3-x}\)</p>
<p>Domain of g(x) is</p>
<p>3 &#8211; x ≥ 0</p>
<p>i.e. x ≤ 3  i.e. A = (-∞, 3].</p>
<p>and domain of \(f(g(x))  =  (3-x)^{\frac{1}{4}}\)</p>
<p>3 &#8211; x ≥ 0</p>
<p>i.e. x ≤ 3  i.e. B = (-∞, 3].</p>
<p>Here, A∩B = (-∞, 3] is domain of fog.</p>
<p><strong>Range:</strong></p>
<p>\(y = (3-x)^{\frac{1}{4}}\)</p>
<p><sup>4</sup>√y = 3 &#8211; x</p>
<p>x  = 3 &#8211; <sup>4</sup>√y</p>
<p>x exists for y &gt; 0 but domain limit is (-∞, 3]</p>
<p>Range will be (0, 3]</p>
</div>
<h3>Question (b)</h3>
<div><p><p>A rectangular storage container with an open top has a volume of 20m<sup>3</sup>. The length of its base is twice its width. Material for the base costs Rs.10 per square meter material for the sides costs Rs 4 per square meter. Express the cost of materials as a function of the width of the base.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Let x = the width and  h = the height of the container.</p>
<p>Volume V = 2x<sup>2</sup>h = 20</p>
<p>y = 10/x<sup>2</sup></p>
<p>Cost, C = 10 (2x<sup>2</sup>) + 4(2•2xy + 2xy)</p>
<p>=20x<sup>2</sup>+24xy</p>
<p>=20x<sup>2</sup>+24x(10/x<sup>2</sup>)</p>
<p><strong>C(x) = 20x</strong><sup><strong>2</strong></sup><strong>+240/x</strong></p>
</div>
<h3>Question 2(a)</h3>
<div><p><p>Using rectangular, estimate the area under the parabola y = x<sup>2</sup> from 0 to 1.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-17961" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/math.jpg?resize=250%2C384&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="250" height="384"></p>
</div>
<h3>Question (b)</h3>
<div><p><p>A particle moves along a line so that its velocity v at time t is</p>
<p>v = t<sup>2</sup> – t + 6</p>
<ol>
<li>Find the displacement of the particle during the time period 1 ≤ t ≤ 4.</li>
<li>Find the distance travelled during this time period.</li>
</ol</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Solution:</p>
<p>Given,</p>
<p>v = t<sup>2</sup> &#8211; t + 6</p>
<p><strong>a) </strong></p>
<p>As we know,</p>
<p>v = ds / dt</p>
<p>ds = v . dt</p>
<p>Integrating both side,</p>
<p>\(\int ds = \int v \enspace dt\)</p>
<p>Now, We will integrate in the interval  [1, 4]</p>
<p>\(\int_{1}^{4} ds = \int_{1}^{4} v \enspace dt\)</p>
<p>\( = \int_{1}^{4} (t^2 &#8211; t + 6) \enspace dt\)</p>
<p>\( = \left [ \frac{t^3}{3} &#8211; \frac{t^2}{2} + 6t \right ]_{1}^{4}\)</p>
<p>\(= \left [ \frac{64}{3} &#8211; 8 + 24 \right ] &#8211; \left [ \frac{1}{3} &#8211; \frac{1}{2} + 6 \right ]\)</p>
<p>= 112/3 &#8211; 35/6</p>
<p>= 63/2</p>
<p>Therefore, displacement travelled by particle is -9/2 m</p>
<p><strong>b)</strong></p>
<p>Since, distance travelled so, V = 0</p>
<p>then, t<sup>2</sup> &#8211; t + 6 = 0</p>
<p>or, (t &#8211; 3)(t + 2) = 0</p>
<p>or, t = 3, -2</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 3(a)</h3>
<div><p><p>Find the area of the region bounded by y = x<sup>2</sup> and y = 2x – x<sup>2</sup></p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Solution:</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-3779 alignright" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/graph.png?resize=252%2C194&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="252" height="194"></p>
<p>First we will sketch two curves in figure. The limit of integration are found by solving y = 2x &#8211; x<sup>2</sup> and  y = x<sup>2</sup> simultaneously for x.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">or, x<sup>2</sup> = 2x &#8211; x<sup>2</sup></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">or, 2x<sup>2</sup> &#8211; 2x = 0</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">or, x = 0,1</p>
<p>The region runs from x = -1 and x =2. the limit of integration are n = -1, b = 2. The area between the curves is</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">\(A = \int_{a}^{b} [f(x) &#8211; g(x)]dx\)</p>
<p>\( = \int_{0}^{1} [2x &#8211; x^2 &#8211; x^2]dx\)</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">\( = \int_{0}^{1} [2x &#8211; 2x^2]dx\)</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">\(=\left [ \frac{2x^2}{2} &#8211; \frac{2x^3}{3} \right ]_{0}^{1}\)</p>
<p>\(=\left [ x^2 &#8211; \frac{2x^3}{3} \right ]_{0}^{1}\)</p>
<p>\(=1 &#8211; \frac{2}{3}\)</p>
<p>\(= \frac{1}{3}\)</p>
</div>
<h3>Question (b)</h3>
<div><p><p>Using trapezoidal rule, approximate \(\int_{1}^{2}\frac{1}{x}dx\) with n = 5</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Solution:</p>
<p>When n = 5, and b = 2, we have Δx = (2-1)/5 = 0.2, and so the Trapezoidal Rules gives</p>
<p>\(\int^2_1\frac{1}{x}dx = T_{5}\)</p>
<p>= 0.2 / 2 [f(1) + 2f(1.2) + 2f(1.4) + 2f(1.6) + 2f(1.8) + f(2)]</p>
<p>\(= 0.1 \times \left ( \frac{1}{1} + \frac{2}{1.2} + \frac{2}{1.4} + \frac{2}{1.6} + \frac{2}{1.8} + \frac{1}{2} \right )\)</p>
<p>= 0.0695635</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 4(a)</h3>
<div><p><p>Solve y’ = x<sup>2</sup>/y<sup>2</sup>, y(0) = 2</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>Given</p>
<p>\(\frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{x^2}{y^2}\) and given condition y'(0) = 2</p>
<p>\(y^2 \frac{dy}{dx} = x^2\) &#8212;&#8212; (i)</p>
<p>let v = y<sup>3</sup></p>
<p>Differentiating w.r.t x, we get</p>
<p>\(\frac{dv}{dx} = 3y^2 \frac{dy}{dx}\)</p>
<p>\(\frac{1}{3}\frac{dv}{dx} = y^2 \frac{dy}{dx}\)</p>
<p>So, Eq<sup>n</sup> (i) becomes,</p>
<p>\(or, \enspace \frac{1}{3}\frac{dv}{dx} = x^2\)</p>
<p>\(or, \enspace \frac{dv}{dx} = 3x^2])</p>
<p>comparing it with \(\frac{dy}{dx} + Py = Q\), we get</p>
<p>P = 0 and Q = 3x<sup>2</sup></p>
<p>Here, The integral factor (I.F.) is</p>
<p>\(I.F. = e^{\int P dx} = 1\)</p>
<p>Now, the solution of the given differential equation is</p>
<p>y × I.F. = ∫ (Q × I.F.) dx + C</p>
<p>v = ∫ 3x<sup>2 </sup>dx + c</p>
<p>y<sup>3</sup> = x<sup>3</sup> + c</p>
<p>Now,</p>
<p>Given condition is y(0) = 2 so,</p>
<p>2<sup>3</sup> = 0<sup>3</sup> + c</p>
<p>c = 8</p>
<p>Hence, the required solution is</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">y<sup>3</sup> = x<sup>3</sup> + 8</p>
</div>
